A while back I built a small side project and felt proud when login worked token generated, header attached, done. Three weeks later I realized the token never expired, had no refresh logic, and nobody was actually verifying it on protected routes. Anyone holding that token could’ve used my API forever. Fun realization to have at midnight.
Here’s what I learned the hard way.
A JWT isn’t some sealed secret, it’s just base64 text anyone can decode in seconds. The signature is what proves it wasn’t tampered with, so never put sensitive data in the payload.
Don’t store tokens in localStorage. It’s the easy option, but it’s wide open to XSS. An httpOnly cookie is safer since JavaScript can’t touch it.
Give access tokens a short life 15 minutes or so paired with a longer refresh token. If one leaks, the damage window stays small.
And actually verify the token on protected routes, don’t just check it exists:
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');function authenticate(req, res, next) {
const token = req.cookies.accessToken;
if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ message: 'No token provided' });
jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, (err, decoded) => {
if (err) return res.status(403).json({ message: 'Invalid or expired token' });
req.user = decoded;
next();
});
}
Also use a long, random JWT_SECRET, keep it in env variables, and rotate it if it's ever exposed.
None of this is hard, it just doesn’t feel urgent until something breaks. Take the extra thirty minutes now so you’re not debugging it at midnight later.
